Differential Expression Analysis

Perform differential expression analysis between doxorubicin-treated cells vs control cells using limma-voom approach (pay attention to the direction of comparison here.)

levels(as.factor(x$samples$response))
## [1] "Ctrl" "Doxo"
group <- as.factor(x$samples$response)

design <- model.matrix(~0 + group)
x <- estimateDisp(x, design)

v <- voom(x, design, plot = TRUE)

summary(v)
##         Length Class      Mode   
## targets     7  data.frame list   
## E       74814  -none-     numeric
## weights 74814  -none-     numeric
## design     12  -none-     numeric
vfit <- lmFit(v, design)
summary(vfit)
##                  Length Class  Mode     
## coefficients     24938  -none- numeric  
## stdev.unscaled   24938  -none- numeric  
## sigma            12469  -none- numeric  
## df.residual      12469  -none- numeric  
## cov.coefficients     4  -none- numeric  
## pivot                2  -none- numeric  
## rank                 1  -none- numeric  
## Amean            12469  -none- numeric  
## method               1  -none- character
## design              12  -none- numeric
efit <- eBayes(vfit)

summary(decideTests(efit))
##        groupCtrl groupDoxo
## Down         268       166
## NotSig       609       408
## Up         11592     11895
tfit <- treat(vfit, lfc=1) # 2 fold up/downregulation threshold

dt <- decideTests(tfit)
summary(dt)
##        groupCtrl groupDoxo
## Down           0         0
## NotSig      1599      1185
## Up         10870     11284

## [1] 10674

plotMD(tfit, column=1, status=dt[,1], main=colnames(tfit)[1])

Distance matrix using voom-normalized data

sampleDists <- dist(t(v$E))

sampleDistMatrix <- as.matrix(sampleDists)
rownames(sampleDistMatrix) <- col_df$response
colnames(sampleDistMatrix) <- col_df$response
colors <- colorRampPalette( rev(brewer.pal(9, "Blues")) )(255)
pheatmap(sampleDistMatrix,
         # clustering_distance_rows = sampleDists,
         # clustering_distance_cols = sampleDists,
         col = colors, show_rownames = T, show_colnames = T)

100 most upregulated genes

Examine the 100 most upregulated genes in your analysis and compare them with your analysis using DESeq from Week-8. How many are common in two approaches?

DESeq2 Results

# construct DESeq data set
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = cts,
                              colData = col_df,
                              design = ~ response)
dds$response <- factor(dds$response, levels = c("Ctrl", "Doxo"))
rownames(dds) <- gene_names

# filter out lowly expressed genes
keep <- rowSums(counts(dds) >= 10) >= min(summary(factor(dds$response)))
dds <- dds[keep, ]

dds <- DESeq(dds)
res <- results(dds, contrast = c("response", "Ctrl", "Doxo"))

upregulated_des_100 <- head(res[order(-res$log2FoldChange, decreasing = TRUE), ], 100)
upregulated_lim_100 <- head(upregulated_lim, 100)
venn.plot <- venn.diagram(
  x = list(rownames(upregulated_lim_100), rownames(upregulated_des_100)),
  category.names = c("Limma", "DESeq"),
  filename = NULL,
  output = TRUE)

grid.draw(venn.plot)

Genes upregulated by limma but not by DESeq2

up_genes_lim <- rownames(upregulated_lim[upregulated_lim$adj.P.Val < 0.05 & upregulated_lim$logFC > 0, ])
up_genes_des <- rownames(subset(res, padj < 0.05 & log2FoldChange > 0))

length(setdiff(up_genes_lim, up_genes_des))
## [1] 5635

Genes upregulated by DESeq2 but not by limma

length(setdiff(up_genes_des, up_genes_lim))
## [1] 383
